result.execSummary:
The defendant Anthony Randolph Quesenberry was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 9:33 Defendant Anthony Randolph Quesenberry via phone in court with attorney Andrew Martin Nelson.  William H. Thorie appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Thorie files amended information. Court goes over the Def's right to be present in court. Def understands he has that right and is waiving that right and wants to appear via phone. Thorie guilty to charge contained in amended information. Fine of $265.60. Nelson and Def agree.   Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form is filed with the court; court reviews with Def. Def is currently in the service. Def pleas no contest to amended charge in amended information; Nelson stipulates to factual basis.   COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS. Court finds and adjudicates Def guilty of amended charge. Nelson addresses sentencing. Court accepts recommendation and orders a $265.60 fine, due in 30 days.  Appeal rights are given to the defendant.
